let x = 10;


Youâ€™ll get an error:

ReferenceError: Cannot access 'x' before initialization


But why? ğŸ¤”
Letâ€™s break it down â¬‡ï¸

ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Memory Creation Phase (Hoisting Phase)

When JavaScript starts executing code, it first creates memory space for all variables and functions.

Hereâ€™s what happens:

var â†’ is hoisted and initialized with undefined

let and const â†’ are hoisted, but NOT initialized âŒ

So memory looks like this:

var a = undefined
let x = (uninitialized)
const y = (uninitialized)

ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Execution Phase

Now JavaScript executes the code line by line:

When it reaches console.log(x),
the variable x already exists in memory,
but itâ€™s not yet initialized â€”
this period is called the Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ) âš¡

Once the line let x = 10; runs,
x finally gets its value, and the TDZ ends âœ…

ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Visualize It ğŸ¨
Line	Code	Description
1	console.log(x)	âŒ Error â€” x is in TDZ
2	let x = 10	âœ… TDZ ends here
3	console.log(x)	âœ… Prints 10
ğŸ”¹ Step 4: When Does TDZ Occur?
Variable Type	Hoisted?	Has TDZ?	Default Value
var	âœ… Yes	âŒ No	undefined
let	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes	uninitialized
const	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes	uninitialized
ğŸ”¹ Step 5: TDZ in Function Expressions

Example:

