const sayHi = function() {
  console.log("Hi");
};


Explanation:

sayHi is declared with const.

Itâ€™s hoisted but not initialized yet.

When JS tries to call it before initialization,
itâ€™s still in the TDZ, so you get an error:

Cannot access 'sayHi' before initialization

ğŸ”¹ Step 6: Real-life Example ğŸ³

Imagine youâ€™re in a kitchen:

A bowl is already kept on the counter (variable is reserved).

But you havenâ€™t put any food inside it yet (value not assigned).

If someone tries to eat from that bowl â€” âŒ error!

That empty waiting time before filling the bowl is the Temporal Dead Zone ğŸ˜„

ğŸ”¹ Step 7: Summary Table
Concept	Meaning
Hoisting	All variables/functions are stored in memory before execution
TDZ	The time period when let or const variables exist in memory but cannot be accessed
Why it exists?	To prevent accidental use of variables before they are properly initialized


Step 10: In Short (Interview Line)

IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression)
is a JavaScript function that executes immediately after being defined.
Itâ€™s mainly used to create a private scope, avoid global variable conflicts, and execute setup logic right away.

Agar chaaho to main iska visual explanation (flow diagram) bana du â€”
jisme dikhaun:

